sec.p:
The fibrin fiber was modelled as it was done previously21,22 with several simplifications. The fiber composed of N equally spaced nodes connected by elastic springs (see Supplementary Fig. 2A). The spring equilibrium length was L and it was equal to the initial distance between nodes. The fiber was located in the XY-plane and the angle α between fiber and x-axis was variable (Table 1). The motion of the node i in solution was described by the second Newton’s law of motion. The system was assumed to be in an overdamped regime (mä = 0):

(1)

η⋅r˙i=Fi,i−1+Fi,i+1+FiB
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \eta \cdot \dot{r}_{i}=F_{i, i-1}+F_{i, i+1}+F_{i}^{B}$$\end{document}



where ri was the position vector of the node i in three-dimensional coordinates (x,y,z); η was the drag coefficient for the fiber node in the blood serum; Fi,i−1 = Kr · (Δri,i−1 − L) and Fi,i+1 = Kr · (Δri,i+1 − L) were the vector forces which acted on the node i from the node i-1 or i+1 according to the Hook’s law due to the spring elongation or shortening (Δri,i−1 and Δri,i+1 was the distance between nodes i and i-1 or the nodes i and i+1; Kr was the fiber spring constant); FiB\begin{document}$F_{i}^{B}$\end{document} was the Brownian force which acted on the node i due to thermal fluctuations. To solve the equations for the nodes in solution, the system of equations was discretized and the Heun’s method was used. According to this method, the evolution of coordinates in time for the differential equation

(2)

x˙=f(x,t)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \dot{x}=f(x, t)$$\end{document}



was calculated using a two-step algorithm:

(3)

x~n+1=xn+Δt⋅f(xn,tn)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \tilde{x}^{n+1}=x^{n}+\Delta t \cdot f\left(x^{n}, t^{n}\right)$$\end{document}




(4)

xn+1=xn+Δt2⋅{f(xn,tn)+f(x~n+1,tn+1)}
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle x^{n+1}=x^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{2} \cdot\left\{f\left(x^{n}, t^{n}\right)+f\left(\tilde{x}^{n+1}, t^{n+1}\right)\right\}$$\end{document}



where Δt was the time step used in calculation and discretization scheme; tn+1 = tn + Δt; xn was coordinate at the tn moment of time.

Thus, the evolution of the node i coordinates in time was calculated according to a two-step process (in a vector form):
(5)
r~in+1=rin+Δtη⋅(Fi,i−1(rin,ri−1n)+Fi,i+1(rin,ri+1n)+Fin,B) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \tilde{r}_{i}^{n+1}=r_{i}^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{\eta} \cdot\left(F_{i, i-1}\left(r_{i}^{n}, r_{i-1}^{n}\right)+F_{i, i+1}\left(r_{i}^{n}, r_{i+1}^{n}\right)+F_{i}^{n, B}\right)$$\end{document}
(6)
rin+1=rin+Δt2η⋅(Fi,i−1(rin,ri−1n)+Fi,i+1(rin,ri+1n)+Fin,B+Fi,i−1(r~in+1,r~i−1n+1)+Fi,i+1(r~in+1,r~i+1n+1)+F~in+1,B) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & \quad r_{i}^{n+1}=r_{i}^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{2 \eta} \cdot\left(F_{i, i-1}\left(r_{i}^{n}, r_{i-1}^{n}\right)+F_{i, i+1}\left(r_{i}^{n}, r_{i+1}^{n}\right)+F_{i}^{n, B}+F_{i, i-1}\left(\tilde{r}_{i}^{n+1}, \tilde{r}_{i-1}^{n+1}\right)+\right. \\ & \left.F_{i, i+1}\left(\tilde{r}_{i}^{n+1}, \tilde{r}_{i+1}^{n+1}\right)+\widetilde{F}_{i}^{n+1, B}\right)\end{aligned}$$\end{document}
